November 10, 2019 With v0.24.0, WTF now has better support for theme-like colour settings. It&rsquo;s far from perfect, a lot of modules will have to be improved internally to make theming ubiquitous, but it&rsquo;s a start.
By way of example, if you&rsquo;re running v0.24 or later, drop this into your config at the top, replace your existing colors: YAML block with the following and you&rsquo;ll end up with a facsimile of an old-school green monochrome monitor display (you may need to restart WTF to get changes to take effect).
Copy   colors: background: &#34;transparent&#34; border: focusable: &#34;lightgreen&#34; focused: &#34;goldenrod&#34; normal: &#34;darkgreen&#34; checked: &#34;gray&#34; highlight: fore: &#34;black&#34; back: &#34;green&#34; labels: &#34;lightgreen::b&#34; rows: even: &#34;green&#34; odd: &#34;lightgreen&#34; subheading: &#34;lightgreen::b&#34; text: &#34;green&#34; title: &#34;lightgreen&#34;

Quick Start  &nbsp;
WTF is the personal information dashboard for your terminal.
Use WTF to monitor systems, services, and important information that you don&rsquo;t always need visible, but do want to check in on every now and then.
Keep an eye on your OpsGenie schedules, Google Calendar, Git and GitHub repositories, and New Relic deployments.
See who&rsquo;s away in BambooHR, which Jira tickets are assigned to you, what time it is in Barcelona, and dozens more.
&nbsp;
 Follow along on with WTF on Twitter to track changes, fixes, and new releases      Modules are the magic  Modules are the heart of WTF, and WTF comes with over 50 easily-configurable built-in modules. See below for just a few of them.  Then click on Modules to see the complete list. &nbsp;
Git  View the status of your currently-active branch, interact with it, and see all the files you've changed so far.  view module   GitHub  View the status of your remote GitHub repo and interact with it.  view module   Docker  View the current status of Docker on your local machine and interact with it.  view module    Google Calendar  View all your meetings and appointments for days in advance. See any collisions you might have, and which ones you've accepted and rejected.  view module   PagerDuty  See who's currently on-call across multiple teams and multiple schedules. It might even be you.  view module   DigitalOcean  View all your active droplets. Reboot, shut down, or destroy them.  view module    Pi-hole  Enable and disable Pi-hole from the terminal, view the current status, and see all of your blocking stats in one location.  view module   Weather  You could look out your window, but that's cheating. Instead, see it right there in your terminal in text form the way nature intended.  view module   Transmission  Start, stop, pause your downloads and view your seeding stats. It's easy to keep track of all your Linux ISO downloads now.  view module    and dozens more! Sponsors make it happen Sponsoring is a great way to show your support for WTF, and WTF is proud to participate in the GitHub Sponsors program.
If WTF occupies that special place in your terminal, please consider sponsoring its ongoing development. It makes a difference.
